Yeah, Foreman's clearly wrong.

499
00:33:31,710 --> 00:33:33,872
You're clearly not
grasping at straws,

500
00:33:33,945 --> 00:33:36,039
because you're clearly
not emotionally involved.

501
00:33:36,681 --> 00:33:38,513
I know you want to
believe this is something

502
00:33:38,583 --> 00:33:42,247
we can cure.
It's not. I'm sorry.

503
00:33:54,299 --> 00:33:56,859
How soon will they
know if it's cancer?

504
00:33:56,935 --> 00:33:58,597
Within hours.

505
00:33:59,738 --> 00:34:01,036
And if it is?

506
00:34:02,807 --> 00:34:04,139
There's always chemo.

507
00:34:05,443 --> 00:34:07,469
You say that like
it's not gonna work.

508
00:34:08,947 --> 00:34:10,245
It could extend your life.

509
00:34:11,016 --> 00:34:12,348
Years?

510
00:34:17,889 --> 00:34:19,585
I'll be here as
much as you need.

511
00:34:23,728 --> 00:34:26,823
You still never told me
why you left the seminary.

512
00:34:30,168 --> 00:34:31,727
Mary Knoller.

513
00:34:32,270 --> 00:34:34,432
Wife of the groundskeeper.

514
00:34:35,907 --> 00:34:38,934
He caught me with
her, got me with a rake.

515
00:34:39,010 --> 00:34:42,469
Those scars on my ass
you may have noticed...

516
00:34:43,748 --> 00:34:45,580
Why didn't you
tell me that before?

517
00:34:45,650 --> 00:34:47,312
Because it was so shallow.

518
00:34:47,419 --> 00:34:50,947
I wasn't exactly wrestling
with great theological questions.

519
00:34:51,923 --> 00:34:53,255
I don't believe that.

520
00:34:53,959 --> 00:34:55,759
You don't sleep with
the groundskeeper's wife,

521
00:34:55,794 --> 00:34:59,162
not unless you're struggling
with whether you belong there.

522
00:35:03,001 --> 00:35:07,496
I always wanted to believe.
Would've made my life a lot easier.

523
00:35:09,474 --> 00:35:11,033
It never took.

524
00:35:12,477 --> 00:35:13,501
Doesn't

525
00:35:14,279 --> 00:35:15,303
mean

526
00:35:16,648 --> 00:35:18,480
it's too late.

527
00:35:18,550 --> 00:35:20,416
Are you having trouble
talking, like before?

528
00:35:22,687 --> 00:35:24,986
I can get the words out...

529
00:35:25,390 --> 00:35:27,291
Just feels heavy when I do.

530
00:35:27,626 --> 00:35:28,753
Where?

531
00:35:28,827 --> 00:35:32,594
Wherever my chewing muscles are.

532
00:35:33,999 --> 00:35:35,331
I'll be right back.

533
00:35:40,405 --> 00:35:42,067
House finally got you?

534
00:35:42,173 --> 00:35:43,607
He tried, but... I gotta go.

535
00:35:43,708 --> 00:35:46,109
You should have
seen it, it was perfect.

536
00:35:50,348 --> 00:35:51,839
She has jaw claudication.

537
00:35:53,084 --> 00:35:55,284
If you only heard claudication
and carotid dissection...

538
00:35:55,954 --> 00:35:57,946
I'd say giant cell arteritis,

539
00:35:59,190 --> 00:36:02,285
and I'd tell your former
teammates to put her on steroids.

540
00:36:03,094 --> 00:36:04,187
She's gonna live.

541
00:36:05,296 --> 00:36:06,355
Yeah.

542
00:36:07,132 --> 00:36:08,259
And then what?

543
00:36:14,873 --> 00:36:16,553
They say my liver
function's better,

544
00:36:17,042 --> 00:36:18,322
that I can get out of here soon.

545
00:36:19,210 --> 00:36:22,305
And when you do, I want to
take you to Puerto Escondido.

546
00:36:23,381 --> 00:36:24,405
Mexico?

547
00:36:24,549 --> 00:36:25,608
The Mexican Pipeline.

548
00:36:26,084 --> 00:36:28,952
Early May is when the
surf really picks up, but...

549
00:36:32,090 --> 00:36:33,251
What's wrong?

550
00:36:35,160 --> 00:36:36,628
I spoke to the prioress...

551
00:36:37,562 --> 00:36:38,655
You're going back?

552
00:36:39,497 --> 00:36:40,863
I felt the calling.

553
00:36:41,900 --> 00:36:42,993
When you saw the boy?

554
00:36:43,334 --> 00:36:48,671
I felt God's love, his grace. I've
been waiting my entire life for that.

555
00:36:48,773 --> 00:36:50,002
It's not real.

556
00:36:50,108 --> 00:36:53,237
I know you didn't feel anything
when you almost died. I did.

557
00:36:53,311 --> 00:36:57,806
You felt oxygen deprivation, you
felt your brain releasing noradrenaline.

558
00:36:58,416 --> 00:36:59,782
You didn't say that before.

559
00:37:00,285 --> 00:37:03,278
I wanted you to
move on with your life.

560
00:37:03,354 --> 00:37:06,256
I wanted to reassure you.
I wanted you to feel better.

561
00:37:06,791 --> 00:37:08,453
And now you don't?

562
00:37:08,827 --> 00:37:10,352
Now...

563
00:37:12,831 --> 00:37:13,924
I think I love you.

564
00:37:25,510 --> 00:37:30,881
"Noradrenaline and Near-Death
Experiences." Oh, dear.

565
00:37:30,982 --> 00:37:32,075
You saw God?

566
00:37:32,884 --> 00:37:36,321
She did. She wants to
go back to the monastery.

567
00:37:36,387 --> 00:37:38,879
And now you're preparing
a PowerPoint presentation

568
00:37:38,990 --> 00:37:42,119
to keep her in your
garden of earthly delights.

569
00:37:42,193 --> 00:37:44,025
You're an idiot.

570
00:37:44,662 --> 00:37:46,494
Because I've found
someone I love?

571
00:37:46,631 --> 00:37:48,463
Because you're an idiot.

572
00:37:48,533 --> 00:37:50,695
At least you two
have that in common.

573
00:37:50,802 --> 00:37:53,795
Her feelings are based on a chemical
process. They're gonna wear off.

574
00:37:54,239 --> 00:37:58,074
You just slept with her, your
brain is exploding with oxytocin.

575
00:37:58,176 --> 00:37:59,854
You think that's gonna
last through the ages?

576
00:37:59,878 --> 00:38:02,074
She's throwing away her
life because of blind faith.

577
00:38:02,180 --> 00:38:03,307
So are you.

578
00:38:04,549 --> 00:38:07,075
She's found something she
wants to build her life around.

579
00:38:07,585 --> 00:38:09,679
It's a total illusion, but
apparently she'll take

580
00:38:09,754 --> 00:38:11,031
a little ignorance
with her bliss.

581
00:38:11,055 --> 00:38:12,580
And you want to take that away.

582
00:38:12,690 --> 00:38:15,125
How many times have you
thrown the truth in people's faces?

583
00:38:15,226 --> 00:38:16,922
Because it's the
truth. Not because

584
00:38:17,061 --> 00:38:18,791
we're gonna live
happily ever after.

585
00:38:20,565 --> 00:38:22,864
Either your relationship
just blows up

586
00:38:23,001 --> 00:38:25,300
like every other
non-magical romance,

587
00:38:25,403 --> 00:38:27,201
or she stays with
you but blames you for

588
00:38:27,272 --> 00:38:29,298
stripping all the
meaning out of her life.

589
00:38:29,641 --> 00:38:32,634
This has nothing
to do with the truth.

590
00:38:32,744 --> 00:38:35,213
You don't like that
I'm reassessing my life,

591
00:38:35,346 --> 00:38:37,815
that I want to
change it, that I can.

592
00:38:37,916 --> 00:38:40,977
Anyone can screw up a life. I
never said that wasn't possible.

593
00:38:41,085 --> 00:38:43,077
You're incapable of
human connection,

594
00:38:43,221 --> 00:38:45,247
so you want everyone
to be like you.

595
00:38:46,958 --> 00:38:48,551
If I wanted you to be like me,

596
00:38:52,897 --> 00:38:57,232
I would be urging you to make
a stupid, stubborn decision

597
00:38:57,302 --> 00:39:00,170
that blows up your life and
leaves you lonely and miserable.

598
00:39:06,644 --> 00:39:10,081
You reassess your life
when you've made mistakes.

599
00:39:10,148 --> 00:39:12,515
You didn't. You
just got stabbed.

600
00:40:12,744 --> 00:40:14,542
Don't look at the book.

601
00:40:14,612 --> 00:40:17,047
I haven't done a jugular
line since my residency,

602
00:40:17,115 --> 00:40:19,380
I don't want to
needle the carotid.

603
00:40:23,021 --> 00:40:24,080
What's the first step?

604
00:40:25,757 --> 00:40:28,124
Palpate the SCM. Where?

605
00:40:29,394 --> 00:40:31,056
Middle third of the neck.

606
00:41:02,393 --> 00:41:03,622
I'm happy I knew you.

607
00:41:05,630 --> 00:41:06,996
So am I.

608
00:41:23,815 --> 00:41:25,010
Robert.

609
00:42:22,173 --> 00:42:24,213
Twenty-four-year-old
water treatment worker

610
00:42:24,242 --> 00:42:26,211
with pyrexia and double vision.

611
00:42:27,145 --> 00:42:28,545
A mystery.

612
00:42:29,680 --> 00:42:32,411
How'd he get sick
working in a sewer?

613
00:42:32,517 --> 00:42:34,509
Ed Norton was the
picture of health.

614
00:42:48,366 --> 00:42:49,425
Abscess?

615
00:42:49,901 --> 00:42:51,927
Would have seen it on the MRI.

616
00:42:52,036 --> 00:42:54,198
Diphtheria paralyzing
the ocular muscles?

617
00:42:54,472 --> 00:42:57,032
No, paralysis was
first. Aneurysm?
